<subSubSection pageId="207" pageNumber="485" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="207.[728,1319,298,726]" lastBlockId="207.[113,1319,732,1159]" pageId="207" pageNumber="485">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[728,986,342,371]" pageId="207" pageNumber="485">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 103 mm, tail 133 mm, hindfoot 22 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. The Lesser Colombian Climbing Rat is small, with bright orange-brown dorsum and cream or pale orange hair tips over dark gray bases on venter. Tail is longer than head-body length and medium to dark brown, with hairs lengthening over distal 25% and terminating in moderately long pencil (10-15 mm). Ears are very dark. Hindfeet are short and proportionately narrower than in most other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tschudi" authorityYear="1845" box="[623,771,775,804]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Rhipidomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="207" pageNumber="485" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rhipidomys</taxonomicName>
, with poorly defined dorsal dark patch that contrasts sharply with pale digits.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
